
1. Notes from LinkedIn course:- On B2B sales foundation
URL - https://www.linkedin.com/learning/b2b-sales-foundations/defining-b2b-sales?autoplay=true&resume=false
	a. B2B = Business to business & B2C = Business to consumer 
	b. Know the customers "Procurement rules", their "Budget Cycles" & "Key influencers"
	c. Good sales people are:
		Thick skinned
		Confident
		Resilient
	d. Skills to be successful:
		Attracting prospects
		Qualifying leads
		Educating buyers on your products & services
		Listening for buyer needs
		Building conceptual agreement
		Closing deals
		Asking for referrals
	 e. Maintain a Win/Loss record 
		 Outreach
		 Progress
		 Conclusions
	 f. "If you are not being rejected then you are not trying hard enough"
	 g. Define your best customer. Don't chase every lead. You will get better customer lifecycle value.
	 i. Make a list of customers ranked by overall spend. What attributes do they share?
	 j. How to find your customers:
		 -> Get help from marketing dept
		 -> Or Sales team which reaches out to prospects
		 -> Warm referrals (nurture existing relationships)
		 -> Attend events, local conferences, chamber of commerce
	  k. Check if a potential customer has the MANDate
		  -> Money (Do they have budget now)
		  -> Authority (to buy)
		  -> Need (for the product or service you are selling)
		  -> Desire (to buy)
	 l. Great initial prospect meeting:
		 -> Don't overinvest in the pitch deck (your company already has it, try to understand the customer first)
		 -> Online decision making moment - ZMOT (Zero moment of truth, is when the prospect researches the product before buying)
		 -> Ask the prospect - "What are their goals and expectations"
		 -> First meeting is to understand their desired destination.
	 m. Handling Objections from Prospects:
		 -> Objections are normal. They help you understand the prospects needs better.
		 -> They might not understand your product's value.
		 -> Or they might be needing a feature that's needed in your product.
		 -> If they are objecting, that means they are considering your offer. That's good news.
		 -> Objections generate conversations that build trust and understanding.
	 n. Always make sure to have "Conceptual understanding"
		 -> Fancy way of saying - "the prospect has told you that if you make a contract with details as discussed and within price range as discussed then they are ready to sign".
	 o. Stay in touch after the deal closes.
	 p. How you can be measured:
		 -> High level sales goal
		 -> Number of new customer sales
		 -> Sales per product line
		 -> "Pipeline report" is your best friend. Its a doc that tracks prospective deals.
		 -> In pipeline report - Deals are labelled according to what milestone you have achieved so far.
			 Opportunity level established?
			 Conceptual agreement with stakeholders?
			 Proposal written?
			 Signed agreement?
			 Asked for referrals?
		 -> Report - also defines where you are in the sales process with each prospect.
		 Also estimates the expected deal size. It lays the odds of each deal closing.
		 -> Your pipeline can quickly tell you what your expected sales are for the quarter.
		 -> Number crunching (hypothetical scenario):
			 a. Annual sales quota = $1,000,000
			 b. Avg deal size = $ 50,000
			 c. Deals needed = 20
			 d. Proposals needed = 50
			 e. Opportunities needed = 100 
			 f. Conversations needed = 600
			 That is 150 conversations per quarter.
			 12 weeks per quarter.
			 So new prospect calls per week = 12 to 13 calls
			 Adjust the ratios as per your scenario, maybe you need 60 proposals instead of 50 to close 20 deals.
	 q. How to handle missed sales goals?
		 Understand why?
		 Ask for feedback.
		 Accept consequences
		 Learn from experience
		 Dust yourself and move on.
	 r. If you are starting in B2B sales:
		 Talk to as many people as possible who are in Sales
		 "Selling into companies" & "Solution Sales" courses on LinkedIn
		 
	
